import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Healthcare Providers"
  description="How doctors, dentists, and other clinicians can work problem gambling prevention into routine care — brief screening, intervention, coding, and warm handoff in about 90 seconds at the bedside."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/professionals">← Professionals</a>
      </p>
      <h1>Healthcare Providers</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        How doctors, dentists, and other clinicians can work problem gambling
        prevention into routine care — in about 90 seconds at the bedside.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <p>
        Most patients with a gambling problem are never asked about it during a
        clinical encounter. The condition is under-screened, under-coded, and
        often masked by what looks like a primary problem in mood, sleep, or
        substance use. A brief screen takes about 30 seconds; a brief
        intervention takes another minute or two. A single direct question
        from a trusted clinician can change a help-seeking trajectory.
      </p>

      <h2>Why this matters at the point of care</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling Disorder shows up in primary care, urgent care, dental
        visits, and the ED — usually dressed as something else. Unexplained
        financial distress. New-onset insomnia. A ramping anxiety presentation.
        A patient missing appointments after a stretch of attending reliably.
        A partner who says <em>something's off</em> and a patient who avoids
        eye contact when money comes up. Any of these is reason to ask one
        direct, neutral question.
      </p>
      <p>
        Suicide risk in this population is elevated roughly 15–20× over the
        general adult population — comparable to or exceeding the risk in
        moderate-to-severe alcohol use disorder. Naming that risk in your
        screening flow is a clinical safety decision, not a stylistic one.
      </p>

      <h2>30-second screen at the bedside</h2>
      <p>
        Two brief public-domain instruments fit a clinical encounter. Either
        is appropriate; choose by workflow fit.
      </p>

      <h3>Lie/Bet (2 items, Johnson 1997)</h3>
      <p>
        A "yes" to either item is a positive screen and warrants a longer
        assessment.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>Have you ever had to lie to people important to you about how much
          you gambled?</li>
        <li>Have you ever felt the need to bet more and more money?</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>BBGS — Brief Biosocial Gambling Screen (3 items)</h3>
      <p>
        Slightly more sensitive than Lie/Bet; takes about 45 seconds. A "yes"
        to any item is a positive screen.
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li>During the past 12 months, have you become restless, irritable, or
          anxious when trying to stop or cut down on gambling?</li>
        <li>During the past 12 months, have you tried to keep your family or
          friends from knowing how much you gambled?</li>
        <li>During the past 12 months, did you have financial trouble as a
          result of your gambling that you had to get help with from family,
          friends, or welfare?</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Co-occurring conditions to widen the differential</h2>
      <p>
        Gambling Disorder rarely appears alone. When the screen is positive,
        widen the assessment to include:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Mood</strong> — major depressive disorder; bipolar
          (manic / hypomanic episodes can drive betting).</li>
        <li><strong>Anxiety</strong> — generalized anxiety, panic.</li>
        <li><strong>Substance use disorders</strong> — particularly alcohol
          and stimulants; co-occurrence is the rule, not the exception.</li>
        <li><strong>ADHD</strong> — impulsivity and reward-system sensitivity
          overlap significantly.</li>
        <li><strong>Suicidality</strong> — screen explicitly. The Columbia
          Suicide Severity Rating Scale (C-SSRS) fits a brief encounter.</li>
        <li><strong>Trauma / PTSD</strong> — particularly relevant in veteran
          and survivor populations.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Medications worth knowing about</h2>
      <p>
        Two prescribing patterns are well-documented as risk-elevators for new
        or worsening gambling behavior. Worth raising in any med review when a
        patient screens positive.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Dopamine agonists</strong> (pramipexole, ropinirole,
          rotigotine) — used in Parkinson's disease and restless legs
          syndrome, and associated with new-onset compulsive behaviors
          including gambling, hypersexuality, and binge eating in a meaningful
          minority of patients.</li>
        <li><strong>Aripiprazole</strong> (and related D2/D3 partial agonists)
          — carries an FDA-labeled warning about pathological gambling and
          other impulse-control disorders.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        If a patient on one of these medications screens positive, coordinate
        with the prescriber before changes. A switch to a different class
        often resolves the behavior, but abrupt discontinuation has its own
        risks.
      </p>

      <h2>A 60-second brief intervention</h2>
      <p>
        Motivational interviewing principles fit the bedside time budget. A
        usable scaffold:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Ask permission and reflect.</strong> "Is it okay if I
          share what I'm noticing?" Then state the screen result neutrally:
          "Your answers today suggest gambling has started causing some real
          problems."</li>
        <li><strong>Elicit their take.</strong> "What's it like for you to
          hear that?" Listen — don't fill the silence.</li>
        <li><strong>Offer one concrete next step.</strong> "Would it be okay
          if I gave you a number you can call any time — free, confidential,
          and they have people who specifically work with this?" Hand them
          the helpline.</li>
        <li><strong>Document and follow up.</strong> Schedule a recall visit
          within two weeks. Patients given a recall appointment for
          gambling-specific concerns return at rates comparable to other
          chronic-disease follow-ups.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Coding pointers</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>ICD-10-CM:</strong> F63.0 — Pathological gambling.</li>
        <li><strong>DSM-5-TR:</strong> Gambling Disorder, with severity
          specifiers (mild / moderate / severe based on number of criteria
          met).</li>
        <li><strong>CPT screening codes:</strong> The brief-screening codes
          you use for SBIRT in alcohol and substance use (G0442 / G0443;
          99408 / 99409) generally apply when gambling is the focus, where
          coverage allows. Confirm with your payer.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What to give the patient before they leave</h2>
      <p>
        The most useful single artifact is a phone number written on a card
        that fits in a wallet. The National Problem Gambling Helpline is
        free, confidential, available 24/7, and routes to specialists in
        gambling-related concerns.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Call or text 1-800-MY-RESET</strong> (1-800-697-3738).</li>
        <li><strong>Call or text 988</strong> for the Suicide and Crisis
          Lifeline. Gambling-related callers can request a gambling-specific
          counselor.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        We don't maintain a treatment-provider directory on this site. The
        helpline routes patients to in-network, appropriate providers in
        their area without the patient having to navigate that themselves.
      </p>

      <p class="fine-print">
        Coming soon: EHR-importable SmartPhrase blocks for the screens above,
        a printable pocket card, and a free 1.0 CME module on gambling at the
        point of care.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
